# Kurator web + API vs mobile (separate repos)

## Repository layout

- **This repository** hosts the Kurator **web app** and **HTTP API** (source of truth for product behavior, **UI design**, **features**, and **API contracts**).
- The **mobile app** lives in a **separate repository** and is **downstream**: it should follow and stay aligned with the web + API unless the product explicitly diverges.

## For agents working on the mobile app

Whenever the user asks for a **change or feature** that touches the mobile client (or parity with Kurator on web/API), **start by reading all upstream memory files** from **this Kurator repository** at its root:

- **`memory.md`**
- **`memory-flutter-ui-port.md`** (and any other **`memory*.md`** files that exist)

Treat them as the **canonical product and implementation notes** exported from the web/API side. If your workspace does not include that repo, use a linked checkout, submodule, or ask the user to provide paths—**do not guess** behavior or visuals that memory documents.

## For agents working in this repository (web + API)

When you change something the mobile app is expected to mirror, keep **documentation, tests, Swagger, and memory** updated per **`change-completeness.mdc`**, and note **downstream mobile impact** when the change is user-facing or contract-changing so owners can sync the other repo.

## Mobile-only Cursor workspace

Cursor loads **`.cursor/rules/`** from the **open project**. To give mobile-repo agents the same instruction, **copy this file** into the mobile app repository as **`.cursor/rules/upstream-mobile-downstream.mdc`** (same body; keep `alwaysApply: true`). In that copy, adjust wording if needed so “this repository” clearly means the **Kurator web+API** checkout (e.g. sibling path or submodule) where **`memory*.md`** live.
